Here's the complete `MauiProgram.cs` registration:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    // Services — Singleton: one shared instance across the entire app
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

    // ViewModels — Transient: fresh state on every navigation
    builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
    builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

    // Pages — Transient: constructor injection fires each time
    builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
    builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Type | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Talks to a REST API — expensive to create, holds shared `HttpClient`/config, no per-page state. One instance is reused app-wide. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | ViewModels hold page-specific state. A fresh instance on each navigation prevents stale data from a previous visit. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Ensures constructor injection runs every time Shell resolves the page, wiring up the fresh ViewModel. |

**Wire each Page to its ViewModel via constructor injection:**

```csharp
public partial class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage(MainViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = viewModel;
    }
}
```

**Key pitfall to avoid:** Don't register ViewModels as Singleton — they'll keep stale state across navigations. And don't use `AddScoped` — MAUI has no built-in request scope, so it silently behaves as Singleton.
